      <abstract>
        <p>Let <italic>G</italic> be a simple graph of order <italic>n</italic> and <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup"><italic>A</italic>(<italic>G</italic>)</textual-form><mml:math id="M1" altimg="si1.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula> be its adjacency matrix. The nullity of a graph <italic>G</italic>, denoted by <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup">Œ∑(<italic>G</italic>)</textual-form><mml:math id="M2" altimg="si2.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>Œ∑</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>, is the multiplicity of the eigenvalue zero in the spectrum of <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup"><italic>A</italic>(<italic>G</italic>)</textual-form><mml:math id="M3" altimg="si3.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>A</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>. Denote by <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup">ùíû<sub><italic>k</italic></sub></textual-form><mml:math id="M4" altimg="si4.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="script">C</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup">‚Ñí<sub><italic>k</italic></sub></textual-form><mml:math id="M5" altimg="si5.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="script">L</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula> the set of all connected graphs with <italic>k</italic> induced cycles and the set of line graphs of all graphs in <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup">ùíû<sub><italic>k</italic></sub></textual-form><mml:math id="M6" altimg="si6.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="script">C</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>, respectively. In 1998, Sciriha [I. Sciriha, On singular line graphs of trees, Congr. Numer. 135 (1998) 73‚Äì91] show that the order of every tree whose line graph is singular is even. Then Gutman and Sciriha [I. Gutman, I. Sciriha, On the nullity of line graphs of trees, Discrete Math. 232 (2001) 35‚Äì45] show that the nullity set of <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup">‚Ñí<sub>0</sub></textual-form><mml:math id="M7" altimg="si7.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="script">L</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula> is <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup">{0,1}</textual-form><mml:math id="M8" altimg="si8.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">{</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mtext>,</mml:mtext><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">}</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>. In this paper, we investigate the nullity of graphs with cut-points and deduce some concise formulas. Then we generalize Scirihas‚Äô result, showing that the order of every graph <italic>G</italic> is even if such a graph <italic>G</italic> satisfies that <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup"><italic>G</italic>‚ààùíû<sub><italic>k</italic></sub></textual-form><mml:math id="M9" altimg="si9.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo>‚àà</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="script">C</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup">Œ∑(<italic>L</italic>(<italic>G</italic>)) = <italic>k</italic> + 1</textual-form><mml:math id="M10" altimg="si10.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>Œ∑</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>L</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>, and the nullity set of <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup">‚Ñí<sub><italic>k</italic></sub></textual-form><mml:math id="M11" altimg="si11.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="script">L</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula> is <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup">{0,1,‚Ä¶,<italic>k</italic>,<italic>k</italic> + 1}</textual-form><mml:math id="M12" altimg="si12.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">{</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mtext>,</mml:mtext><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mtext>,</mml:mtext><mml:mo>‚Ä¶</mml:mo><mml:mtext>,</mml:mtext><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mtext>,</mml:mtext><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">}</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula> for any given <italic>k</italic>, where <inline-formula><alternatives><textual-form specific-use="jats-markup"><italic>L</italic>(<italic>G</italic>)</textual-form><mml:math id="M13" altimg="si13.gif" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>L</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula> denotes the line graph of the graph <italic>G</italic>.</p>
